    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1955-07-16T03:15:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1955-07-16T03:15:00-05:00" n="172"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d172">
                <head>172. Memorandum of a Conversation, Quai d’Orsay, Paris, July 16, 1955, 9:15
                        a.m.<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d172fn1">Source: Department of State,
                        Conference Files: Lot 63 D 123, CF 494. Confidential.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Paris</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1955-07-16T09:15:00+01:00"
                            >July 16, 1955, 9:15 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPANTS</head>
                    <item>Foreign Minister <persName corresp="#p_PA1">Pinay</persName> and three
                        members of his staff</item>
                    <item>Messrs. <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Stassen</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_BRR1">Robert Bowie</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_TWR1">William Tyler</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>In response to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PA1">Pinay</persName>’s request, Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Stassen</persName> discussed certain preliminary
                    results of the U.S. disarmament studies, in accordance with the points outlined
                    in the July 11, 1955 letter<note n="2" xml:id="d172fn2">
                        <ref target="#d152">Document 152</ref>.</note> to the Secretary of State and
                    the Secretary’s concurrence of July 14th [<hi rend="italic">13th</hi>].<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d172fn3">See <ref target="#d152fn2">footnote 2</ref>, <hi
                            rend="italic">ibid</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PA1">Pinay</persName> expressed agreement that reliance
                    must be placed upon the inspection system and not upon any treaty, as such, and
                    that the free world must maintain a posture and legal right such that if an
                    agreement is violated, the free world would not have any less security than they
                    would have had in the absence of an agreement.</p>
                <pb facs="0365" n="339" xml:id="pg_339"/>
                <p>He asked whether the Soviet was aware of the progress the U.S. has made in
                    nuclear weapons and of U.S. progress in early warning and defense against
                    attack. He was advised they undoubtedly had considerable awareness, but probably
                    were not completely cognizant.</p>
                <p>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PA1">Pinay</persName> expressed great interest in the
                    objectives of disarmament; asked that Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SHE1"
                        >Stassen</persName> confer with Mr. <persName>Jules Moch</persName>;<note
                        n="4" xml:id="d172fn4">
                        <persName>Jules Moch</persName>, French Permanent Representative at the U.N.
                        Disarmament Commission.</note> indicated a preference for no separate talks
                    with Mr. <persName>Palewski</persName>;<note n="5" xml:id="d172fn5">
                        <persName>Gaston Palewski</persName>, Deputy Minister to the President of
                        the French Council.</note> and expressed the hope that he might have a
                    further conference with Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">Stassen</persName> some
                    time after Geneva.</p>
                <p>He emphasized the importance of the free nations standing together and of
                    including Germany in the free world association.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SHE1">
                            <hi rend="strong">HES</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
